    'excerpt' => 'A clear, up-to-date breakdown of what a website really costs in Australia in 2026 — from DIY builders to full agency builds — plus the ongoing hosting and maintenance fees most quotes quietly leave out.',
    'keywords' => 'website cost australia, how much does a website cost, website pricing australia, small business website cost, web design cost australia, website maintenance cost',
    'meta_title' => 'Website Cost Australia: 2026 Pricing Guide',
    'meta_description' => 'Website cost Australia 2026: real price ranges for DIY, freelancer and agency builds, plus the ongoing hosting and maintenance fees. A plain-English guide for owners.',
    'body' => '<p>If you want the short answer: in 2026, the typical <strong>website cost in Australia</strong> for a small business sits somewhere between <strong>$1,500 and $15,000</strong> for the build, with most owners landing in the <strong>$3,000 to $8,000</strong> range for a professional, several-page site that actually brings in enquiries. A simple do-it-yourself site can cost almost nothing up front, while a large custom build or online store can run well past $30,000. The range is so wide because "a website" can mean anything from a one-page holding page to a booking system with payments, member logins and hundreds of products.</p>

<p>That spread is frustrating when you are just trying to set a budget. So in this guide we break down exactly what you pay for, what a fair price looks like at each level, and — just as importantly — the ongoing website costs that most quotes conveniently leave out. No jargon, no upsell, just the honest numbers an Australian small business owner needs to plan properly.</p>

<h2>What does a website cost in Australia in 2026?</h2>

<p>The single biggest factor in price is <em>who builds it</em> and <em>how custom it is</em>. Below is a realistic snapshot of what different approaches cost this year. These are build (one-off) figures in Australian dollars, based on typical market rates — your exact quote will move up or down with complexity.</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Approach</th>
<th>Typical build cost</th>
<th>Best for</th>
</tr>
</thead>
